This epithet stands last, as summing up the beneficent character of the Muses, which has been the theme of the first half of the Ode, and as leading us by the association of contrast to the impersonations of brute and insensate force, whose vain efforts and doom are the subject of the latter half.

The universality of Jove's rule is indicated not only by the nouns ‘ terram‚' ⁶ mare,’ etc. which describe his triple empire in earth, in Hades, in heaven, but also by the triple contrast os the epithets ex- pressed or implied: the ‘dull earth' (‘bruta‚' 1. 34. 9) and the ‘sea stirred by every wind‚' ⁶ the [busy] eities of the living and the sad realm of the shades,⁷ ‘the [‘ quieti ordines' of the] gods and the turmoil of niortal men.¹ However much they differ in all else, they are all alike subject to his sway. For Horace‘s manner of marking a contrast by giving an epithet to one only of the two things contrasted see on 2. 3. 9, 3. 13. 7, 4. 4. 10. Note also that the epithets actually given are all such as imply some difficulty or unlikelihood in the way os his rule. He can sway the earth‚ however insensate it be; the sea, however stormy; the sad shadow-world‚ as well as the world of men; the turmoil of earth, as well as the quiet gods.
